# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: software-defined-networking
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] In network routing, the **control plane** is the part of the router architecture that is concerned with establishing the network topology, or the information in a routing table that defines what to do with incoming packets.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] Control plane functions, such as participating in routing protocols, run in the architectural control element.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] In most cases, the routing table contains a list of destination addresses and the outgoing interface or interfaces associated with each.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] Control plane logic can also identify certain packets to be discarded, as well as preferential treatment of certain packets for which a high quality of service is defined by such mechanisms as differentiated services.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] Depending on the specific router implementation, there may be a separate forwarding information base that is populated by the control plane, but used by the high-speed forwarding plane to look up packets and decide how to handle them.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] In computing, the control plane is the part of the software that configures and shuts down the data plane.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] By contrast, the data plane is the part of the software that processes the data requests.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] The data plane is also sometimes referred to as the forwarding plane.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] The distinction has proven useful in the networking field where it originated, as it separates the concerns: the data plane is optimized for speed of processing, and for simplicity and regularity.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] The control plane is optimized for customizability, handling policies, handling exceptional situations, and in general facilitating and simplifying the data plane processing.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] A major function of the control plane is deciding which routes go into the main routing table.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] "Main" refers to the table that holds the unicast routes that are active.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] Multicast routing may require an additional routing table for multicast routes.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] Several routing protocols e.g., IS-IS, OSPF and BGP maintain internal databases of candidate routes which are promoted when a route fails or when a routing policy is changed.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] Several different information sources may provide information about a route to a given destination, but the router must select the "best" route to install into the routing table.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] In some cases, there may be multiple routes of equal "quality", and the router may install all of them and load-share across them.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] Routers forward traffic that enters on an input interface and leaves on an output interface, subject to filtering and other local rules.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] While routers usually forward from one physical (e.g., Ethernet, serial) to another physical interface, it is also possible to define multiple logical interfaces on a physical interface.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] A physical Ethernet interface, for example, can have logical interfaces in several virtual LANs defined by IEEE 802.1Q VLAN headers.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] When an interface has an address configured in a subnet, such as 192.0.2.1 in the 192.0.2.0/24 (i.e., subnet mask 255.255.255.0) subnet, and that interface is considered "up" by the router, the router thus has a directly connected route to 192.0.2.0/24.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] If a routing protocol offered another router's route to that same subnet, the routing table installation software will normally ignore the dynamic route and prefer the directly connected route.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] There also may be software-only interfaces on the router, which it treats as if they were locally connected.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] For example, most implementations have a "null" software-defined interface.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] Packets having this interface as a next hop will be discarded, which can be a very efficient way to filter traffic.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] Routers usually can route traffic faster than they can examine it and compare it to filters, so, if the criterion for discarding is the packet's destination address, "blackholing" the traffic will be more efficient than explicit filters.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] Other software-defined interfaces that are treated as directly connected, as long as they are active, are interfaces associated with tunneling protocols such as Generic Routing Encapsulation (GRE) or Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS).
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] Loopback interfaces are virtual interfaces that are considered directly connected interfaces.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] Router configuration rules may contain static routes.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] A static route minimally has a destination address, a prefix length or subnet mask, and a definition of where to send packets for the route.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] That definition can refer to a local interface on the router, or a next-hop address that could be on the far end of a subnet to which the router is connected.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] The next-hop address could also be on a subnet that is directly connected, and, before the router can determine if the static route is usable, it must do a **recursive lookup** of the next hop address in the local routing table.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] If the next-hop address is reachable, the static route is usable, but if the next-hop is unreachable, the route is ignored.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] Static routes also may have preference factors used to select the best static route to the same destination.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] One application is called a **floating static route**, where the static route is less preferred than a route from any routing protocol.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] The static route, which might use a dial-up link or other slow medium, activates only when the dynamic routing protocol(s) cannot provide a route to the destination.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] Static routes that are more preferred than any dynamic route can also be very useful, especially when using traffic engineering principles to make certain traffic go over a specific path with an engineered quality of service.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] The routing table manager, according to implementation and configuration rules, may select a particular route or routes from those advertised by various routing protocols.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] Different implementations have different sets of preferences for routing information, and these are not standardized among IP routers.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] It is fair to say that subnets on directly connected active interfaces are always preferred.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] Beyond that, however, there will be differences.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] Implementers generally have a numerical preference, which Cisco calls an "administrative distance", for route selection.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] The lower the preference, the more desirable the route.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] Cisco's IOS implementation makes exterior BGP the most preferred source of dynamic routing information, while Nortel RS makes intra-area OSPF most preferred.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] If the route is "more specific" than an existing route, install it in addition to the existing routes.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] "More specific" means that it has a longer prefix.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] If the route is of equal specificity to a route already in the routing table, but comes from a more preferred source of routing information, replace the route in the table.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] If the routes are of equal metric and the router supports load-sharing, add the new route and designate it as part of a load-sharing group.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] Typically, implementations will support a maximum number of routes that load-share to the same destination.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] If that maximum is already in the table, the new route is usually dropped.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] See forwarding plane for more detail, but each implementation has its own means of updating the forwarding information base (FIB) with new routes installed in the routing table.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] If the FIB is in one-to-one correspondence with the RIB, the new route is installed in the FIB after it is in the RIB.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] If the FIB is smaller than the RIB, and the FIB uses a hash table or other data structure that does not easily update, the existing FIB might be invalidated and replaced with a new one computed from the updated RIB.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] Multicast routing builds on unicast routing.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] Each multicast group to which the local router can route has a multicast routing table entry with a next hop for the group, rather than for a specific destination as in unicast routing.
[src:software-defined-networking/control-plane] There can be multicast static routes as well as learning dynamic multicast routes from a protocol such as Protocol Independent Multicast (PIM).
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] In routing, the **data plane**, sometimes called the **forwarding plane** or **user plane**, defines the part of the router architecture that determines what to do with packets arriving on an inbound interface.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] Most commonly, it refers to a table in which the router looks up the destination address of the incoming packet and retrieves the information necessary to determine the path from the receiving element, through the internal **forwarding fabric** of the router, and to the proper outgoing interface(s).
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] In certain cases the table may specify that a packet is to be discarded.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] In such cases, the router may return an ICMP "destination unreachable" or other appropriate code.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] Some security policies, however, dictate that the router should drop the packet silently, in order that a potential attacker does not become aware that a target is being protected.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] The incoming forwarding element will also decrement the time-to-live (TTL) field of the packet, and, if the new value is zero, discard the packet.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] Before or after examining the destination, other tables may be consulted to determine how to handle packets based on other characteristics, such as the source address, the IP protocol identifier field, or Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) or User Datagram Protocol (UDP) port number.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] Forwarding plane functions run in the forwarding element.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] High-performance routers often have multiple distributed forwarding elements, so that the router increases performance with parallel processing.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] The outgoing interface will encapsulate the packet in the appropriate data link protocol.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] Depending on the router software and its configuration, functions, usually implemented at the outgoing interface, may set various packet fields, such as the DSCP field used by differentiated services.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] In general, the passage from the input interface directly to an output interface, through the fabric with minimum modification at the output interface, is called the *fast path* of the router.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] If the packet needs significant processing, such as segmentation or encryption, it may go onto a slower path, which is sometimes called the *services plane* of the router.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] Service planes can make forwarding or processing decisions based on higher-layer information, such as a Web URL contained in the packet payload.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] The *data plane* is the part of the software that processes the data requests.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] By contrast, the control plane is the part of the software that configures and shuts down the data plane.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] The conceptual separation of the data plane from the control plane has been done for years.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] An early example is Unix, where the basic file operations are open, close for the control plane and read, write for the data plane.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] The conceptual separation of the data plane from the control plane in software programming has proven useful in the packet switching field where it originated.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] In networking, the data plane is sometimes referred to as the forwarding plane, as it separates the concerns: the data plane is optimized for speed of processing, and for simplicity and regularity.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] The control plane is optimized so as to allow configuration, handling policies, handling exceptional situations, and in general facilitating and simplifying the data plane processing.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] Vendors design router products for specific markets.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] Design of routers intended for home use, perhaps supporting several PCs and VoIP telephony, is driven by keeping the cost as low as possible.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] In such a router, there is no separate forwarding fabric, and there is only one active forwarding path: into the main processor and out of the main processor.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] Routers for more demanding applications accept greater cost and complexity to get higher throughput in their forwarding planes.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] Routers may have one or more processors.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] In a uniprocessor design, these performance parameters are affected not just by the processor speed, but by competition for the processor.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] Higher-performance routers invariably have multiple processing elements, which may be general-purpose processor chips or specialized application-specific integrated circuits (ASIC).
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] Very high performance products have multiple processing elements on each interface card.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] In such designs, the main processor does not participate in forwarding, but only in control plane and management processing.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] In the Internet Engineering Task Force, two working groups in the Operations & Maintenance Area deal with aspects of performance.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] The Interprovider Performance Measurement (IPPM) group focuses, as its name would suggest, on operational measurement of services.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] Performance measurements on single routers, or narrowly defined systems of routers, are the province of the Benchmarking Working Group (BMWG).
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] A classic RFC 2544 benchmark uses half the router's (i.e., the device under test (DUT)) ports for input of a defined load, and measures the time at which the outputs appear at the output ports.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] Originally, all destinations were looked up in the RIB.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] Perhaps the first step in speeding routers was to have a separate RIB and FIB in main memory, with the FIB, typically with fewer entries than the RIB, being organized for fast destination lookup.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] In contrast, the RIB was optimized for efficient updating by routing protocols.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] Early uniprocessing routers usually organized the FIB as a hash table, while the RIB might be a linked list.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] Depending on the implementation, the FIB might have fewer entries than the RIB, or the same number.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] When routers started to have separate forwarding processors, these processors usually had far less memory than the main processor, such that the forwarding processor could hold only the most frequently used routes.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] On the early Cisco AGS+ and 7000, for example, the forwarding processor cache could hold approximately 1000 route entries.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] In an enterprise, this would often work quite well, because there were fewer than 1000 server or other popular destination subnets.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] Such a cache, however, was far too small for general Internet routing.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] Different router designs behaved in different ways when a destination was not in the cache.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] A **cache miss** condition might result in the packet being sent back to the main processor, to be looked up in a **slow path** that had access to the full routing table.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] Depending on the router design, a cache miss might cause an update to the fast hardware cache or the fast cache in main memory.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] In some designs, it was most efficient to invalidate the fast cache for a cache miss, send the packet that caused the cache miss through the main processor, and then repopulate the cache with a new table that included the destination that caused the miss.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] This approach is similar to an operating system with virtual memory, which keeps the most recently used information in physical memory.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] As memory costs went down and performance needs went up, FIBs emerged that had the same number of route entries as in the RIB, but arranged for fast lookup rather than fast update.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] Whenever a RIB entry changed, the router changed the corresponding FIB entry.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] High-performance FIBs achieve their speed with implementation-specific combinations of specialized algorithms and hardware.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] Various search algorithms have been used for FIB lookup.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] While well-known general-purpose data structures were first used, such as hash tables, specialized algorithms, optimized for IP addresses, emerged.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] A multicore CPU architecture is commonly used to implement high-performance networking systems.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] These platforms facilitate the use of a software architecture in which the high-performance packet processing is performed within a fast path environment on dedicated cores, in order to maximize system throughput.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] A run-to-completion model minimizes OS overhead and latency.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] Various forms of fast RAM and, eventually, basic content-addressable memory (CAM) were used to speed lookup.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] CAM, while useful in layer 2 switches that needed to look up a relatively small number of fixed-length MAC addresses, had limited utility with IP addresses having variable-length routing prefixes (see Classless Inter-Domain Routing).
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] Ternary CAM (CAM), while expensive, lends itself to variable-length prefix lookups.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] One of the challenges of forwarder lookup design is to minimize the amount of specialized memory needed, and, increasingly, to minimize the power consumed by memory.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] A next step in speeding routers was to have a specialized forwarding processor separate from the main processor.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] There was still a single path, but forwarding no longer had to compete with control in a single processor.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] The fast routing processor typically had a small FIB, with hardware memory (e.g., static random-access memory (SRAM)) faster and more expensive than the FIB in main memory.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] Main memory was generally dynamic random-access memory (DRAM).
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] Next, routers began to have multiple forwarding elements, that communicated through a high-speed **shared bus** or through a **shared memory**.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] Cisco used shared busses until they saturated, while Juniper preferred shared memory.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] Each forwarding element had its own FIB.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] Eventually, the shared resource became a bottleneck, with the limit of shared bus speed being roughly 2 million packets per second (Mpps).
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] Crossbar fabrics broke through this bottleneck.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] As forwarding bandwidth increased, even with the elimination of cache miss overhead, the shared paths limited throughput.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] While a router might have 16 forwarding engines, if there was a single bus, only one packet transfer at a time was possible.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] There were some special cases where a forwarding engine might find that the output interface was one of the logical or physical interfaces present on the forwarder card, such that the packet flow was totally inside the forwarder.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] It was often easier, however, even in this special case, to send the packet out the bus and receive it from the bus.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] While some designs experimented with multiple shared buses, the eventual approach was to adapt the crossbar switch model from telephone switches, in which every forwarding engine had a hardware path to every other forwarding engine.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] With a small number of forwarding engines, crossbar forwarding fabrics are practical and efficient for high-performance routing.
[src:software-defined-networking/forwarding-plane] There are multistage designs for crossbar systems, such as Clos networks.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] NFV relies upon traditional server-virtualization techniques, such as those used in enterprise IT.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] For example, a virtual session border controller could be deployed to protect a network without the typical cost and complexity of obtaining and installing physical network protection units.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] Other examples of NFV include virtualized load balancers, firewalls, intrusion detection devices and WAN accelerators to name a few.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] Decoupling the network function software from the customized hardware platform creates a flexible network architecture that enables agile network management, faster new service roll outs with significant reduction in CAPEX and OPEX.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] Product development within the telecommunication industry has traditionally followed rigorous standards for stability, protocol adherence and quality, reflected by the use of the term carrier grade to designate equipment demonstrating this high reliability and performance factor.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] While this model worked well in the past, it inevitably led to long product cycles, a slow pace of development and reliance on proprietary or specific hardware, e.g., bespoke application-specific integrated circuits (ASICs).
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] In October 2012, a group of telecom operators published a white paper at a conference in Darmstadt, Germany, on software-defined networking (SDN) and OpenFlow.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] The Call for Action concluding the White Paper led to the creation of the Network Functions Virtualization (NFV) Industry Specification Group (ISG) within the European Telecommunications Standards Institute (ETSI).
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] The ISG was made up of representatives from the telecommunication industry from Europe and beyond.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] ETSI ISG NFV addresses many aspects, including functional architecture, information model, data model, protocols, APIs, testing, reliability, security, future evolutions, etc.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] The ETSI ISG NFV has announced the Release 5 of its specifications since May 2021 aiming to produce new specifications and extend the already published specifications based on new features and enhancements.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] Since the publication of the white paper, the group has produced over 100 publications, which have gained wider acceptance in the industry and are being implemented in prominent open source projects like OpenStack, ONAP, Open Source MANO (OSM) to name a few.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] Due to active cross-liaison activities, the ETSI NFV specifications are also being referenced in other SDOs like 3GPP, IETF, ETSI MEC etc.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] Network functions virtualization infrastructure (NFVI) is the totality of all hardware and software components that build the environment where NFVs are deployed.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] The NFV infrastructure can span several locations.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] The network providing connectivity between these locations is considered as part of the NFV infrastructure.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] The building block for both the NFVI and the NFV-MANO is the NFV platform.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] In the NFVI role, it consists of both virtual and physical processing and storage resources, and virtualization software.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] In its NFV-MANO role it consists of VNF and NFVI managers and virtualization software operating on a hardware controller.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] The NFV platform implements carrier-grade features used to manage and monitor the platform components, recover from failures and provide effective security – all required for the public carrier network.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] A service provider that follows the NFV design implements one or more virtualized network functions, or *VNFs*.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] A VNF by itself does not automatically provide a usable product or service to the provider's customers.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] To build more complex services, the notion of *service chaining* is used, where multiple VNFs are used in sequence to deliver a service.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] Another aspect of implementing NFV is the *orchestration* process.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] To build highly reliable and scalable services, NFV requires that the network be able to instantiate VNF instances, monitor them, repair them, and (most important for a service provider business) bill for the services rendered.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] These attributes, referred to as carrier-grade features, are allocated to an orchestration layer in order to provide high availability and security, and low operation and maintenance costs.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] Importantly, the orchestration layer must be able to manage VNFs irrespective of the underlying technology within the VNF.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] For example, an orchestration layer must be able to manage an SBC VNF from vendor X running on VMware vSphere just as well as an IMS VNF from vendor Y running on KVM.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] The initial perception of NFV was that virtualized capability should be implemented in data centers.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] This approach works in many – but not all – cases.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] NFV presumes and emphasizes the widest possible flexibility as to the physical location of the virtualized functions.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] Ideally, therefore, virtualized functions should be located where they are the most effective and least expensive.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] That means a service provider should be free to locate NFV in all possible locations, from the data center to the network node to the customer premises.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] This approach, known as distributed NFV, has been emphasized from the beginning as NFV was being developed and standardized, and is prominent in the recently released NFV ISG documents.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] For some cases there are clear advantages for a service provider to locate this virtualized functionality at the customer premises.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] These advantages range from economics to performance to the feasibility of the functions being virtualized.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] The first ETSI NFV ISG-approved public multi-vendor proof of concept (PoC) of D-NFV was conducted by Cyan, Inc., RAD, Fortinet and Certes Networks in Chicago in June, 2014, and was sponsored by CenturyLink.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] It was based on RAD's dedicated customer-edge D-NFV equipment running Fortinet's Next Generation Firewall (NGFW) and Certes Networks’ virtual encryption/decryption engine as Virtual Network Functions (VNFs) with Cyan's Blue Planet system orchestrating the entire ecosystem.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] RAD's D-NFV solution, a Layer 2/Layer 3 network termination unit (NTU) equipped with a D-NFV X86 server module that functions as a virtualization engine at the customer edge, became commercially available by the end of that month.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] During 2014 RAD also had organized a D-NFV Alliance, an ecosystem of vendors and international systems integrators specializing in new NFV applications.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] When designing and developing the software that provides the VNFs, vendors may structure that software into software components (implementation view of a software architecture) and package those components into one or more images (deployment view of a software architecture).
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] These vendor-defined software components are called VNF Components (VNFCs).
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] VNFs are implemented with one or more VNFCs and it is assumed, without loss of generality, that VNFC instances map 1:1 to VM Images.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] VNFCs should in general be able to scale up and/or scale out.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] By being able to allocate flexible (virtual) CPUs to each of the VNFC instances, the network management layer can scale up (i.e., scale *vertically*) the VNFC to provide the throughput/performance and scalability expectations over a single system or a single platform.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] Similarly, the network management layer can scale out (i.e., *scale horizontally*) a VNFC by activating multiple instances of such VNFC over multiple platforms and therefore reach out to the performance and architecture specifications whilst not compromising the other VNFC function stabilities.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] Network Functions Virtualisation is highly complementary to SDN.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] In essence, SDN is an approach to building data networking equipment and software that separates and abstracts elements of these systems.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] It does this by decoupling the control plane and data plane from each other, such that the control plane resides centrally and the forwarding components remain distributed.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] The control plane interacts with both northbound and southbound.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] In the northbound direction the control plane provides a common abstracted view of the network to higher-level applications and programs using high-level APIs and novel management paradigms, such as Intent-based networking.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] In the southbound direction the control plane programs the forwarding behavior of the data plane, using device level APIs of the physical network equipment distributed around the network.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] Thus, NFV is not dependent on SDN or SDN concepts, but NFV and SDN can cooperate to enhance the management of a NFV infrastructure and to create a more dynamic network environment.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] It is entirely possible to implement a virtualized network function (VNF) as a standalone entity using existing networking and orchestration paradigms.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] An NFV system needs a central orchestration and management system that takes operator requests associated with an NS or a VNF, translates them into the appropriate processing, storage and network configuration needed to bring the NS or VNF into operation.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] Once in operation, the VNF and the networks it is connected to potentially must be monitored for capacity and utilization, and adapted if necessary.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] All network control functions in an NFV infrastructure can be accomplished using SDN concepts and NFV could be considered one of the primary SDN use cases in service provider environments.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] For example, within each NFV infrastructure site, a VIM could rely upon an SDN controller to set up and configure the overlay networks interconnecting (e.g.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] VXLAN) the VNFs and PNFs composing an NS.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] The SDN controller would then configure the NFV infrastructure switches and routers, as well as the network gateways, as needed.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] Similarly, a Wide Area Infrastructure Manager (WIM) could rely upon an SDN controller to set up overlay networks to interconnect NSs that are deployed to different geo-located NFV infrastructures.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] It is also apparent that many SDN use-cases could incorporate concepts introduced in the NFV initiative.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] Examples include where the centralized controller is controlling a distributed forwarding function that could in fact be also virtualized on existing processing or routing equipment.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] NFV has proven a popular standard even in its infancy.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] Its immediate applications are numerous, such as virtualization of mobile base stations, platform as a service (PaaS), content delivery networks (CDN), fixed access and home environments.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] The potential benefits of NFV is anticipated to be significant.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] Virtualization of network functions deployed on general purpose standardized hardware is expected to reduce capital and operational expenditures, and service and product introduction times.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] Many major network equipment vendors have announced support for NFV.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] This has coincided with NFV announcements from major software suppliers who provide the NFV platforms used by equipment suppliers to build their NFV products.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] However, to realize the anticipated benefits of virtualization, network equipment vendors are improving IT virtualization technology to incorporate carrier-grade attributes required to achieve high availability, scalability, performance, and effective network management capabilities.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] To minimize the total cost of ownership (TCO), carrier-grade features must be implemented as efficiently as possible.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] This requires that NFV solutions make efficient use of redundant resources to achieve five-nines availability (99.999%), and of computing resource without compromising performance predictability.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] The NFV platform is the foundation for achieving efficient carrier-grade NFV solutions.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] It is a software platform running on standard multi-core hardware and built using open source software that incorporates carrier-grade features.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] The NFV platform software is responsible for dynamically reassigning VNFs due to failures and changes in traffic load, and therefore plays an important role in achieving high availability.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] There are numerous initiatives underway to specify, align and promote NFV carrier-grade capabilities such as ETSI NFV Proof of Concept, ATIS Open Platform for NFV Project, Carrier Network Virtualization Awards and various supplier ecosystems.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] The vSwitch, a key component of NFV platforms, is responsible for providing connectivity both VM-to-VM (between VMs) and between VMs and the outside network.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] Its performance determines both the bandwidth of the VNFs and the cost-efficiency of NFV solutions.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] The standard Open vSwitch's (OVS) performance has shortcomings that must be resolved to meet the needs of NFVI solutions.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] Significant performance improvements are being reported by NFV suppliers for both OVS and Accelerated Open vSwitch (AVS) versions.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] Virtualization is also changing the way availability is specified, measured and achieved in NFV solutions.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] As VNFs replace traditional function-dedicated equipment, there is a shift from equipment-based availability to a service-based, end-to-end, layered approach.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] Virtualizing network functions breaks the explicit coupling with specific equipment, therefore availability is defined by the availability of VNF services.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] Because NFV technology can virtualize a wide range of network function types, each with their own service availability expectations, NFV platforms should support a wide range of fault tolerance options.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] This flexibility enables CSPs to optimize their NFV solutions to meet any VNF availability requirement.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] ETSI has already indicated that an important part of controlling the NFV environment be done through automated orchestration.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] NFV Management and Orchestration (NFV-MANO) refers to a set of functions within an NFV system to manage and orchestrate the allocation of virtual infrastructure resources to virtualized network functions (VNFs) and network services (NSs).
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] They are the brains of the NFV system and a key automation enabler.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] The entry point in NFV-MANO for external operations support systems (OSS) and business support systems (BSS) is the NFVO, which is in charge of managing the lifecycle of NS instances.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] The management of the lifecycle of VNF instances constituting an NS instance is delegated by the NFVO to one more or VNFMs.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] Both the NFVO and the VNFMs uses the services exposed by one or more VIMs for allocating virtual infrastructure resources to the objects they manage.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] Additional functions are used for managing containerized VNFs: the Container Infrastructure Service Management (CISM) and the Container Image Registry (CIR) functions.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] The CISM is responsible for maintaining the containerized workloads while the CIR is responsible for storing and maintaining information of OS container software images The behavior of the NFVO and VNFM is driven by the contents of deployment templates (a.k.a.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] NFV descriptors) such as a Network Service Descriptor (NSD) and a VNF Descriptor (VNFD).
