[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] An overview of the different versions of the OpenAPI representations of NFV-MANO APIs is available on the ETSI NFV wiki.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] The OpenAPI files as well as the TOSCA YAML definition files and YANG modules applicable to NFV descriptors are available on the ETSI Forge.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] Recent performance study on NFV focused on the throughput, latency and jitter of virtualized network functions (VNFs), as well as NFV scalability in terms of the number of VNFs a single physical server can support.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] From 2018, many VNF providers began to migrate many of their VNFs to a container-based architecture.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] Such VNFs also known as Cloud-Native Network Functions (CNF) utilize many innovations deployed commonly on internet infrastructure.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] These include auto-scaling, supporting a continuous delivery / DevOps deployment model, and efficiency gains by sharing common services across platforms.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] Through service discovery and orchestration, a network based on CNFs will be more resilient to infrastructure resource failures.
[src:software-defined-networking/network-function-virtualization] Utilizing containers, and thus dispensing with the overhead inherent in traditional virtualization through the elimination of the guest OS can greatly increase infrastructure resource efficiency.
[src:software-defined-networking/openflow] OpenFlow enables network controllers to determine the path of network packets across a network of switches.
[src:software-defined-networking/openflow] The controllers are distinct from the switches.
[src:software-defined-networking/openflow] This separation of the control from the forwarding allows for more sophisticated traffic management than is feasible using access control lists (ACLs) and routing protocols.
[src:software-defined-networking/openflow] Also, OpenFlow allows switches from different vendors — often each with their own proprietary interfaces and scripting languages — to be managed remotely using a single, open protocol.
[src:software-defined-networking/openflow] The protocol's inventors consider OpenFlow an enabler of software-defined networking (SDN).
[src:software-defined-networking/openflow] OpenFlow allows remote administration of a layer 3 switch's packet forwarding tables, by adding, modifying and removing packet matching rules and actions.
[src:software-defined-networking/openflow] Packets which are unmatched by the switch can be forwarded to the controller.
[src:software-defined-networking/openflow] The controller can then decide to modify existing flow table rules on one or more switches or to deploy new rules, to prevent a structural flow of traffic between switch and controller.
[src:software-defined-networking/openflow] It could even decide to forward the traffic itself, provided that it has told the switch to forward entire packets instead of just their header.
[src:software-defined-networking/openflow] The OpenFlow protocol is layered on top of the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) and prescribes the use of Transport Layer Security (TLS).
[src:software-defined-networking/openflow] Controllers should listen on TCP port 6653 for switches that want to set up a connection.
[src:software-defined-networking/openflow] Earlier versions of the OpenFlow protocol unofficially used port 6633.
[src:software-defined-networking/openflow] Some network control plane implementations use the protocol to manage the network forwarding elements.
[src:software-defined-networking/openflow] OpenFlow is mainly used between the switch and controller on a secure channel.
[src:software-defined-networking/openflow] The Open Networking Foundation (ONF), a user-led organization dedicated to promotion and adoption of software-defined networking (SDN), manages the OpenFlow standard.
[src:software-defined-networking/openflow] ONF defines OpenFlow as the first standard communications interface defined between the control and forwarding layers of an SDN architecture.
[src:software-defined-networking/openflow] OpenFlow allows direct access to and manipulation of the forwarding plane of network devices such as switches and routers, both physical and virtual (hypervisor-based).
[src:software-defined-networking/openflow] It is the absence of an open interface to the forwarding plane that has led to the characterization of today's networking devices as monolithic, closed, and mainframe-like.
[src:software-defined-networking/openflow] A protocol like OpenFlow is needed to move network control out of proprietary network switches and into control software that's open source and locally managed.
[src:software-defined-networking/openflow] A number of network switch and router vendors announced intent to support or are shipping supported switches for OpenFlow, including Alcatel-Lucent, Big Switch Networks, Brocade Communications, and Radisys.
[src:software-defined-networking/openflow] Version 1.1 of the OpenFlow protocol was released on 28 February 2011, and new development of the standard was managed by the ONF.
[src:software-defined-networking/openflow] In December 2011, the ONF board approved OpenFlow version 1.2 and published it in February 2012.
[src:software-defined-networking/openflow] The current version of OpenFlow is 1.5.1.
[src:software-defined-networking/openflow] However, version 1.6 has been available since September 2016, but accessible only to ONF's members.
[src:software-defined-networking/openflow] In May 2011, Marvell and Larch Networks announced the availability of an OpenFlow-enabled, fully featured switching solution based on Marvell's networking control stack and the Prestera family of packet processors.
[src:software-defined-networking/openflow] Indiana University in May 2011 launched a SDN Interoperability Lab in conjunction with the ONF to test how well different vendors' software-defined networking and OpenFlow products work together.
[src:software-defined-networking/openflow] In June 2012, Infoblox released LINC, an open-source OpenFlow version 1.2 and 1.3 compliant software switch.
[src:software-defined-networking/openflow] In February 2012, Big Switch Networks released Project Floodlight, an Apache-licensed open-source software OpenFlow Controller, and announced its OpenFlow-based SDN Suite in November of that year, which contains a commercial controller, and virtual switching and tap monitoring applications.
[src:software-defined-networking/openflow] In February 2012, HP said it is supporting the standard on 16 of its Ethernet switch products.
[src:software-defined-networking/openflow] In April 2012, Google's Urs Hölzle described how the company's internal network had been completely re-designed over the previous two years to run under OpenFlow with substantial efficiency improvement.
[src:software-defined-networking/openflow] In January 2013, NEC unveiled a virtual switch for Microsoft's Windows Server 2012 Hyper-V hypervisor, which is designed to bring OpenFlow-based software-defined networking and network virtualisation to those Microsoft environments.
[src:software-defined-networking/software-defined-networking] SDN was commonly associated with the OpenFlow protocol for remote communication with network plane elements to determine the path of network packets across network switches since OpenFlow's emergence in 2011.
[src:software-defined-networking/software-defined-networking] However, since 2012, proprietary systems have also used the term.
[src:software-defined-networking/software-defined-networking] These include Cisco Systems' Open Network Environment and Nicira's network virtualization platform.
[src:software-defined-networking/software-defined-networking] SD-WAN applies similar technology to a wide area network (WAN).
[src:software-defined-networking/software-defined-networking] In addition to WAN use cases, SDN is also increasingly applied in telecom backbones, where it is paired with operational inventory and automation platforms to provide real-time visibility, service assurance, and simplified provisioning across multi-vendor networks.
[src:software-defined-networking/software-defined-networking] The history of SDN principles can be traced back to the separation of the control and data planes first used in public switched telephone networks.
[src:software-defined-networking/software-defined-networking] This provided a manner of simplifying provisioning and management years before the architecture was used in data networks.
[src:software-defined-networking/software-defined-networking] The Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) began considering various ways to decouple the control and data forwarding functions in a proposed interface standard published in 2004 named Forwarding and Control Element Separation (ForCES).
[src:software-defined-networking/software-defined-networking] The ForCES Working Group also proposed a companion SoftRouter architecture.
[src:software-defined-networking/software-defined-networking] Additional early standards from the IETF that pursued separating control from data planes include the Linux Netlink as an IP services protocol, and a path computation element (PCE)-based architecture.
[src:software-defined-networking/software-defined-networking] These early attempts failed to gain traction.
[src:software-defined-networking/software-defined-networking] One reason is that many in the Internet community viewed separating control from data to be risky, especially given the potential for failure in the control plane.
[src:software-defined-networking/software-defined-networking] Another reason is that vendors were concerned that creating standard application programming interfaces (APIs) between the control and data planes would result in increased competition.
[src:software-defined-networking/software-defined-networking] In 2006 a young startup was founded around SDN style network topology and submitted a collection of SDN patents in 2007.
[src:software-defined-networking/software-defined-networking] The use of open-source software in these separated architectures traces its roots to the Ethane project at Stanford's computer science department.
[src:software-defined-networking/software-defined-networking] Ethane's simple switch design led to the creation of OpenFlow, and an API for OpenFlow was first created in 2008.
[src:software-defined-networking/software-defined-networking] In that same year, NOX, an operating system for networks, was created.
[src:software-defined-networking/software-defined-networking] SDN research included emulators such as vSDNEmul, EstiNet, and Mininet.
[src:software-defined-networking/software-defined-networking] Work on OpenFlow continued at Stanford, including with the creation of testbeds to evaluate the use of the protocol in a single campus network, as well as across the WAN as a backbone for connecting multiple campuses.
[src:software-defined-networking/software-defined-networking] In academic settings, there were several research and production networks based on OpenFlow switches from NEC and Hewlett-Packard, as well as those based on Quanta Computer white-boxes starting in about 2009.
[src:software-defined-networking/software-defined-networking] Beyond academia, the first deployments were by Nicira in 2010 to control OVS from Onix, codeveloped with NTT and Google.
[src:software-defined-networking/software-defined-networking] A notable deployment was Google's B4 in 2012.
